# You should look at the following URL's in order to grasp a solid understanding

# http://wiki.nginx.org/Pitfalls
# http://wiki.nginx.org/QuickStart
# http://wiki.nginx.org/Configuration
#
# Generally, you will want to move this file somewhere, and start with a clean

#
# Please see /usr/share/doc/nginx-doc/examples/ for more detailed examples.
##

# research-software.org et al. server configuration
#
server {
        # CUSTOM: Listen to port 80 (http) for both ipv4 and ipv6

	root /var/www/research-software.org;

	# Add index.php to the list if you are using PHP
	index index.html index.htm index.nginx-debian.html;

	server_name research-software.org www.research-software.org;

	location = / {
		# First attempt to serve request as file, then
		# as directory, then fall back to displaying a 404.
		# try_files $uri $uri/ =404;
                return 301 https://research-software.org/citation;
	}

	location /citation {
		try_files $uri $uri/ =404;
	}


    listen [::]:443 ssl ipv6only=on; # managed by Certbot
    listen 443 ssl; # managed by Certbot
    ssl_certificate /etc/letsencrypt/live/dev.sdruskat.net/fullchain.pem; # managed by Certbot
    ssl_certificate_key /etc/letsencrypt/live/dev.sdruskat.net/privkey.pem; # managed by Certbot
    include /etc/letsencrypt/options-ssl-nginx.conf; # managed by Certbot
    ssl_dhparam /etc/letsencrypt/ssl-dhparams.pem; # managed by Certbot

    if ($scheme != "https") {
        return 301 https://$host$request_uri;
    } # managed by Certbot

}

rewrite ^(/.well-known/acme-challenge/.*) $1 break; # managed by Certbot


    if ($host = www.research-software.org) {
        return 301 https://$host$request_uri;
    } # managed by Certbot


    if ($host = research-software.org) {
        return 301 https://$host$request_uri;
    } # managed by Certbot


    listen 80;
    listen [::]:80;

    server_name research-software.org www.research-software.org;
    return 404; # managed by Certbot

	root /var/www/research-software.org;

		# First attempt to serve request as file, then
		# as directory, then fall back to displaying a 404.
		# try_files $uri $uri/ =404;
                return 301 https://research-software.org/citation;
	}

    listen 443 ssl; # managed by Certbot

    ssl_dhparam /etc/letsencrypt/ssl-dhparams.pem; # managed by Certbot

    if ($scheme != "https") {
        return 301 https://$host$request_uri;
    } # managed by Certbot

}

2018-02-21 12:41:59,674:DEBUG:certbot_nginx.parser:Writing nginx conf tree to /etc/nginx/sites-enabled/research-software.org:
##
# You should look at the following URL's in order to grasp a solid understanding
# of Nginx configuration files in order to fully unleash the power of Nginx.
# http://wiki.nginx.org/Pitfalls
# http://wiki.nginx.org/QuickStart
# http://wiki.nginx.org/Configuration
#
# Generally, you will want to move this file somewhere, and start with a clean
# file but keep this around for reference. Or just disable in sites-enabled.
#
# Please see /usr/share/doc/nginx-doc/examples/ for more detailed examples.
##

# research-software.org et al. server configuration
#
server {
        # CUSTOM: Listen to port 80 (http) for both ipv4 and ipv6

	root /var/www/research-software.org;

	# Add index.php to the list if you are using PHP
	index index.html index.htm index.nginx-debian.html;

	server_name research-software.org www.research-software.org;

	location / {
		# First attempt to serve request as file, then
		# as directory, then fall back to displaying a 404.
		try_files $uri $uri/ =404;
	}


    listen [::]:443 ssl ipv6only=on; # managed by Certbot
    listen 443 ssl; # managed by Certbot
    ssl_certificate /etc/letsencrypt/live/dev.sdruskat.net/fullchain.pem; # managed by Certbot
    ssl_certificate_key /etc/letsencrypt/live/dev.sdruskat.net/privkey.pem; # managed by Certbot
    include /etc/letsencrypt/options-ssl-nginx.conf; # managed by Certbot
    ssl_dhparam /etc/letsencrypt/ssl-dhparams.pem; # managed by Certbot

# dev.sdruskat.net server configuration
#
server {
        # CUSTOM: Listen to port 80 (http) for both ipv4 and ipv6
        # CUSTOM: Listen to port 80 (http) for both ipv4 and ipv6

	server_name dev.sdruskat.net;

# Generally, you will want to move this file somewhere, and start with a clean
# file but keep this around for reference. Or just disable in sites-enabled.
#
# Please see /usr/share/doc/nginx-doc/examples/ for more detailed examples.
##

# research-software.org et al. server configuration
#
server {
        # CUSTOM: Listen to port 80 (http) for both ipv4 and ipv6

	root /var/www/research-software.org;

	# Add index.php to the list if you are using PHP
	index index.html index.htm index.nginx-debian.html;

	server_name research-software.org www.research-software.org;

	location / {
		# First attempt to serve request as file, then
		# as directory, then fall back to displaying a 404.
		try_files $uri $uri/ =404;
	}


    listen [::]:443 ssl ipv6only=on; # managed by Certbot
    listen 443 ssl; # managed by Certbot
    ssl_certificate /etc/letsencrypt/live/dev.sdruskat.net/fullchain.pem; # managed by Certbot
    ssl_certificate_key /etc/letsencrypt/live/dev.sdruskat.net/privkey.pem; # managed by Certbot
    include /etc/letsencrypt/options-ssl-nginx.conf; # managed by Certbot
    ssl_dhparam /etc/letsencrypt/ssl-dhparams.pem; # managed by Certbot

    if ($scheme != "https") {
        return 301 https://$host$request_uri;
    } # managed by Certbot


}


server {
    if ($host = www.research-software.org) {
        return 301 https://$host$request_uri;
    } # managed by Certbot


    if ($host = research-software.org) {
        return 301 https://$host$request_uri;
    } # managed by Certbot


    listen 80;
    listen [::]:80;

    server_name research-software.org www.research-software.org;
    return 404; # managed by Certbot
}

# dev.sdruskat.net server configuration
#

        # CUSTOM: Listen to port 80 (http) for both ipv4 and ipv6
        # CUSTOM: Listen to port 80 (http) for both ipv4 and ipv6

		# as directory, then fall back to displaying a 404.

		include proxy_params;
		proxy_pass http://tomcat/lexicon;
	}

##
# You should look at the following URL's in order to grasp a solid understanding
# of Nginx configuration files in order to fully unleash the power of Nginx.
# http://wiki.nginx.org/Pitfalls
# http://wiki.nginx.org/QuickStart
# http://wiki.nginx.org/Configuration
#
# Generally, you will want to move this file somewhere, and start with a clean
# file but keep this around for reference. Or just disable in sites-enabled.
#
# Please see /usr/share/doc/nginx-doc/examples/ for more detailed examples.
##

# research-software.org et al. server configuration
#
server {
        # CUSTOM: Listen to port 80 (http) for both ipv4 and ipv6

	root /var/www/research-software.org;

	# Add index.php to the list if you are using PHP
	index index.html index.htm index.nginx-debian.html;

	server_name forschungssoftware.org www.forschungssoftware.org;

	location = / {
		# First attempt to serve request as file, then
		# as directory, then fall back to displaying a 404.
		# try_files $uri $uri/ =404;
                return 301 https://research-software.org/citation;
	}


 # managed by Certbot

    listen 443 ssl; # managed by Certbot
    ssl_certificate /etc/letsencrypt/live/forschungssoftware.org/fullchain.pem; # managed by Certbot
    ssl_certificate_key /etc/letsencrypt/live/forschungssoftware.org/privkey.pem; # managed by Certbot
    include /etc/letsencrypt/options-ssl-nginx.conf; # managed by Certbot
    ssl_dhparam /etc/letsencrypt/ssl-dhparams.pem; # managed by Certbot



}



server {
    if ($host = www.forschungssoftware.org) {
        return 301 https://$host$request_uri;
    } # managed by Certbot


    if ($host = forschungssoftware.org) {
        return 301 https://$host$request_uri;
    } # managed by Certbot



	server_name forschungssoftware.org www.forschungssoftware.org;
    listen 80;
    return 404; # managed by Certbot




}

pid /run/nginx.pid;

	worker_connections 768;
	# multi_accept on;
}

http {
include /etc/letsencrypt/le_tls_sni_01_cert_challenge.conf;
server_names_hash_bucket_size 128;

	##
	# Basic Settings
	##

	sendfile on;
	tcp_nopush on;
	tcp_nodelay on;
	keepalive_timeout 65;
	types_hash_max_size 2048;
	# server_tokens off;

	# server_names_hash_bucket_size 64;
	# server_name_in_redirect off;

	include /etc/nginx/mime.types;
	default_type application/octet-stream;

	##
	# SSL Settings
	##

	ssl_protocols TLSv1 TLSv1.1 TLSv1.2; # Dropping SSLv3, ref: POODLE
	ssl_prefer_server_ciphers on;

	##
	# Logging Settings
	##

	access_log /var/log/nginx/access.log;
	error_log /var/log/nginx/error.log;

	##
	# Gzip Settings
	##

	gzip on;
	gzip_disable "msie6";

	# gzip_vary on;
	# gzip_proxied any;
	# gzip_comp_level 6;
	# gzip_buffers 16 8k;
	# gzip_http_version 1.1;
	# gzip_types text/plain text/css application/json application/javascript text/xml application/xml application/xml+rss text/javascript;

	##
	# Virtual Host Configs
	##

	include /etc/nginx/conf.d/*.conf;
	include /etc/nginx/sites-enabled/*;
}

# http://wiki.nginx.org/QuickStart

#
# Generally, you will want to move this file somewhere, and start with a clean
# file but keep this around for reference. Or just disable in sites-enabled.
#
# Please see /usr/share/doc/nginx-doc/examples/ for more detailed examples.
##

# research-software.org et al. server configuration
#
server {
        # CUSTOM: Listen to port 80 (http) for both ipv4 and ipv6

	root /var/www/research-software.org;

	# Add index.php to the list if you are using PHP
	index index.html index.htm index.nginx-debian.html;

	server_name research-software.org www.research-software.org;

	location / {
		# First attempt to serve request as file, then
		# as directory, then fall back to displaying a 404.
		try_files $uri $uri/ =404;
	}


    listen [::]:443 ssl ipv6only=on; # managed by Certbot
    listen 443 ssl; # managed by Certbot
    ssl_certificate /etc/letsencrypt/live/dev.sdruskat.net/fullchain.pem; # managed by Certbot
    ssl_certificate_key /etc/letsencrypt/live/dev.sdruskat.net/privkey.pem; # managed by Certbot
    include /etc/letsencrypt/options-ssl-nginx.conf; # managed by Certbot
    ssl_dhparam /etc/letsencrypt/ssl-dhparams.pem; # managed by Certbot

    if ($scheme != "https") {
        return 301 https://$host$request_uri;
    } # managed by Certbot


}

rewrite ^(/.well-known/acme-challenge/.*) $1 break; # managed by Certbot

        return 301 https://$host$request_uri;
    } # managed by Certbot


    if ($host = research-software.org) {
        return 301 https://$host$request_uri;
    } # managed by Certbot


    listen 80;
    listen [::]:80;

    server_name research-software.org www.research-software.org;
    return 404; # managed by Certbot

user www-data;
worker_processes auto;
pid /run/nginx.pid;

events {
	worker_connections 768;
	# multi_accept on;
}

http {
include /etc/letsencrypt/le_tls_sni_01_cert_challenge.conf;
server_names_hash_bucket_size 128;

	##
	# Basic Settings
	##

	sendfile on;
	tcp_nopush on;
	tcp_nodelay on;
	keepalive_timeout 65;
	types_hash_max_size 2048;
	# server_tokens off;

	# server_names_hash_bucket_size 64;
	# server_name_in_redirect off;

	include /etc/nginx/mime.types;
	default_type application/octet-stream;

	##
	# SSL Settings
	##

	ssl_protocols TLSv1 TLSv1.1 TLSv1.2; # Dropping SSLv3, ref: POODLE
	ssl_prefer_server_ciphers on;

	##
	# Logging Settings
	##

	access_log /var/log/nginx/access.log;
	error_log /var/log/nginx/error.log;

	##
	# Gzip Settings
	##

	gzip on;
	gzip_disable "msie6";

	# gzip_vary on;
	# gzip_proxied any;
	# gzip_comp_level 6;
	# gzip_buffers 16 8k;
	# gzip_http_version 1.1;
	# gzip_types text/plain text/css application/json application/javascript text/xml application/xml application/xml+rss text/javascript;

	##
	# Virtual Host Configs
	##

	include /etc/nginx/conf.d/*.conf;
	include /etc/nginx/sites-enabled/*;
}

##
# You should look at the following URL's in order to grasp a solid understanding
# of Nginx configuration files in order to fully unleash the power of Nginx.
# http://wiki.nginx.org/Pitfalls
# http://wiki.nginx.org/QuickStart
# http://wiki.nginx.org/Configuration
#
# Generally, you will want to move this file somewhere, and start with a clean
# file but keep this around for reference. Or just disable in sites-enabled.
#
# Please see /usr/share/doc/nginx-doc/examples/ for more detailed examples.
##

# research-software.org et al. server configuration
#
server {
        # CUSTOM: Listen to port 80 (http) for both ipv4 and ipv6

	root /var/www/research-software.org;

	# Add index.php to the list if you are using PHP
	index index.html index.htm index.nginx-debian.html;

	server_name research-software.org www.research-software.org;

	location / {
		# First attempt to serve request as file, then
		# as directory, then fall back to displaying a 404.
		try_files $uri $uri/ =404;
	}


    listen [::]:443 ssl ipv6only=on; # managed by Certbot
    listen 443 ssl; # managed by Certbot
    ssl_certificate /etc/letsencrypt/live/dev.sdruskat.net/fullchain.pem; # managed by Certbot
    ssl_certificate_key /etc/letsencrypt/live/dev.sdruskat.net/privkey.pem; # managed by Certbot
    include /etc/letsencrypt/options-ssl-nginx.conf; # managed by Certbot
    ssl_dhparam /etc/letsencrypt/ssl-dhparams.pem; # managed by Certbot

    if ($scheme != "https") {
        return 301 https://$host$request_uri;
    } # managed by Certbot


}

        return 301 https://$host$request_uri;
    } # managed by Certbot


    if ($host = research-software.org) {
        return 301 https://$host$request_uri;
    } # managed by Certbot


    listen 80;
    listen [::]:80;

    server_name research-software.org www.research-software.org;
    return 404; # managed by Certbot

user www-data;
worker_processes auto;
pid /run/nginx.pid;

events {
	worker_connections 768;
	# multi_accept on;
}

http {
include /etc/letsencrypt/le_http_01_cert_challenge.conf;
include /etc/letsencrypt/le_tls_sni_01_cert_challenge.conf;
server_names_hash_bucket_size 128;

	##
	# Basic Settings
	##

	sendfile on;
	tcp_nopush on;
	tcp_nodelay on;
	keepalive_timeout 65;
	types_hash_max_size 2048;
	# server_tokens off;

	# server_names_hash_bucket_size 64;
	# server_name_in_redirect off;

	include /etc/nginx/mime.types;
	default_type application/octet-stream;

	##
	# SSL Settings
	##

	ssl_protocols TLSv1 TLSv1.1 TLSv1.2; # Dropping SSLv3, ref: POODLE
	ssl_prefer_server_ciphers on;

	##
	# Logging Settings
	##

	access_log /var/log/nginx/access.log;
	error_log /var/log/nginx/error.log;

	##
	# Gzip Settings
	##

	gzip on;
	gzip_disable "msie6";

	# gzip_vary on;
	# gzip_proxied any;
	# gzip_comp_level 6;
	# gzip_buffers 16 8k;
	# gzip_http_version 1.1;
	# gzip_types text/plain text/css application/json application/javascript text/xml application/xml application/xml+rss text/javascript;

	##
	# Virtual Host Configs
	##

	include /etc/nginx/conf.d/*.conf;
	include /etc/nginx/sites-enabled/*;
}

	# Basic Settings
	##

	tcp_nopush on;
	tcp_nodelay on;
	keepalive_timeout 65;
	types_hash_max_size 2048;
	# server_tokens off;

	# server_names_hash_bucket_size 64;
	# server_name_in_redirect off;

	default_type application/octet-stream;

	##
	# SSL Settings
	##

	ssl_protocols TLSv1 TLSv1.1 TLSv1.2; # Dropping SSLv3, ref: POODLE
	ssl_prefer_server_ciphers on;

	##
	# Logging Settings
	##

	error_log /var/log/nginx/error.log;

	##
	# Gzip Settings
	##

	gzip_disable "msie6";

	# gzip_vary on;
	# gzip_proxied any;
	# gzip_comp_level 6;
	# gzip_buffers 16 8k;
	# gzip_http_version 1.1;

	##
	# Virtual Host Configs
	##

	include /etc/nginx/conf.d/*.conf;
	include /etc/nginx/sites-enabled/*;
}

##
# You should look at the following URL's in order to grasp a solid understanding
# of Nginx configuration files in order to fully unleash the power of Nginx.
# http://wiki.nginx.org/Pitfalls
# http://wiki.nginx.org/QuickStart
# http://wiki.nginx.org/Configuration
#
# Generally, you will want to move this file somewhere, and start with a clean
# file but keep this around for reference. Or just disable in sites-enabled.
#
# Please see /usr/share/doc/nginx-doc/examples/ for more detailed examples.
##

# research-software.org et al. server configuration
#
server {
        # CUSTOM: Listen to port 80 (http) for both ipv4 and ipv6

	root /var/www/research-software.org;

	# Add index.php to the list if you are using PHP
	index index.html index.htm index.nginx-debian.html;

	server_name forschungssoftware.org www.forschungssoftware.org;

	location = / {
		# First attempt to serve request as file, then
		# as directory, then fall back to displaying a 404.
		# try_files $uri $uri/ =404;
                return 301 https://research-software.org/citation;
	}


 # managed by Certbot

    listen 443 ssl; # managed by Certbot
    ssl_certificate /etc/letsencrypt/live/forschungssoftware.org/fullchain.pem; # managed by Certbot
    ssl_certificate_key /etc/letsencrypt/live/forschungssoftware.org/privkey.pem; # managed by Certbot
    include /etc/letsencrypt/options-ssl-nginx.conf; # managed by Certbot
    ssl_dhparam /etc/letsencrypt/ssl-dhparams.pem; # managed by Certbot





}



server {
    if ($host = www.forschungssoftware.org) {
        return 301 https://$host$request_uri;
    } # managed by Certbot


    if ($host = forschungssoftware.org) {
        return 301 https://$host$request_uri;
    } # managed by Certbot



	server_name forschungssoftware.org www.forschungssoftware.org;
    listen 80;
    return 404; # managed by Certbot




}

##
# You should look at the following URL's in order to grasp a solid understanding
# of Nginx configuration files in order to fully unleash the power of Nginx.
# http://wiki.nginx.org/Pitfalls
# http://wiki.nginx.org/QuickStart
# http://wiki.nginx.org/Configuration
#
# Generally, you will want to move this file somewhere, and start with a clean
# file but keep this around for reference. Or just disable in sites-enabled.
#
# Please see /usr/share/doc/nginx-doc/examples/ for more detailed examples.
##

##
# Tomcat setup
##
upstream tomcat {
    server 127.0.0.1:8080 fail_timeout=0;
}

# dev.sdruskat.net server configuration
#
server {
	listen 80 default_server; # Ipv4
	listen [::]:80 ipv6only=on; # IPv6
	
	root /var/www/dev.sdruskat.net;

	# Add index.php to the list if you are using PHP
	index index.html index.nginx-debian.html;

	server_name dev.sdruskat.net;

	location / {
		# First attempt to serve request as file, then
		# as directory, then fall back to displaying a 404.
		try_files $uri $uri/ =404;
	}

	# /lexicon forward to tomcat
	location /lexicon {
		include proxy_params;
		proxy_pass http://tomcat/lexicon;
	}


    listen [::]:443 ssl ipv6only=on; # managed by Certbot
    listen 443 ssl; # managed by Certbot
    ssl_certificate /var/lib/letsencrypt/snakeoil/0009_cert.pem; # managed by Certbot
    ssl_certificate_key /var/lib/letsencrypt/snakeoil/0009_key.pem; # managed by Certbot
    include /etc/letsencrypt/options-ssl-nginx.conf; # managed by Certbot
    ssl_dhparam /etc/letsencrypt/ssl-dhparams.pem; # managed by Certbot
}

# dev.sdruskat.net server configuration
#

	listen 80 default_server; # Ipv4
	listen [::]:80 ipv6only=on; # IPv6

		include proxy_params;

##
# You should look at the following URL's in order to grasp a solid understanding
# of Nginx configuration files in order to fully unleash the power of Nginx.
# http://wiki.nginx.org/Pitfalls
# http://wiki.nginx.org/QuickStart
# http://wiki.nginx.org/Configuration
#
# Generally, you will want to move this file somewhere, and start with a clean
# file but keep this around for reference. Or just disable in sites-enabled.
#
# Please see /usr/share/doc/nginx-doc/examples/ for more detailed examples.
##

#
# dev.sdruskat.net server configuration
#
server {
	listen 80;
	listen [::]:80;

	root /var/www/forschungssoftware.org;

	# Add index.php to the list if you are using PHP
	index index.html index.nginx-debian.html;

	server_name forschungssoftware.org www.forschungssoftware.org;

	location = / {
		# First attempt to serve request as file, then
		# as directory, then fall back to displaying a 404.
		return 301 http://research-software.org/citation;
	}


    listen [::]:443 ssl ipv6only=on; # managed by Certbot
    listen 443 ssl; # managed by Certbot
    ssl_certificate /etc/letsencrypt/live/dev.sdruskat.net/fullchain.pem; # managed by Certbot
    ssl_certificate_key /etc/letsencrypt/live/dev.sdruskat.net/privkey.pem; # managed by Certbot
    include /etc/letsencrypt/options-ssl-nginx.conf; # managed by Certbot

2018-02-23 11:31:49,218:DEBUG:certbot_nginx.parser:Writing nginx conf tree to /etc/nginx/sites-enabled/dev.sdruskat.net:
##
# You should look at the following URL's in order to grasp a solid understanding
# of Nginx configuration files in order to fully unleash the power of Nginx.
# http://wiki.nginx.org/Pitfalls
# http://wiki.nginx.org/QuickStart
# http://wiki.nginx.org/Configuration
#
# Generally, you will want to move this file somewhere, and start with a clean
# file but keep this around for reference. Or just disable in sites-enabled.
#
# Please see /usr/share/doc/nginx-doc/examples/ for more detailed examples.
##

##
# Tomcat setup
##
upstream tomcat {
    server 127.0.0.1:8080 fail_timeout=0;
}

# dev.sdruskat.net server configuration
#
server {
	listen 80 default_server; # Ipv4
	listen [::]:80 ipv6only=on; # IPv6
	
	root /var/www/dev.sdruskat.net;

	# Add index.php to the list if you are using PHP
	index index.html index.nginx-debian.html;

	server_name dev.sdruskat.net;

	location / {
		# First attempt to serve request as file, then
		# as directory, then fall back to displaying a 404.
		try_files $uri $uri/ =404;
	}

	# /lexicon forward to tomcat
	location /lexicon {
		include proxy_params;
		proxy_pass http://tomcat/lexicon;
	}


    listen [::]:443 ssl ipv6only=on; # managed by Certbot
    listen 443 ssl; # managed by Certbot
    ssl_certificate /etc/letsencrypt/live/dev.sdruskat.net/fullchain.pem; # managed by Certbot
    ssl_certificate_key /etc/letsencrypt/live/dev.sdruskat.net/privkey.pem; # managed by Certbot
    include /etc/letsencrypt/options-ssl-nginx.conf; # managed by Certbot
    ssl_dhparam /etc/letsencrypt/ssl-dhparams.pem; # managed by Certbot

}

2018-02-23 11:31:49,333:DEBUG:certbot_nginx.parser:Writing nginx conf tree to /etc/nginx/sites-enabled/dev.sdruskat.net:
##
# You should look at the following URL's in order to grasp a solid understanding
# of Nginx configuration files in order to fully unleash the power of Nginx.
# http://wiki.nginx.org/Pitfalls
# http://wiki.nginx.org/QuickStart
# http://wiki.nginx.org/Configuration
#
# Generally, you will want to move this file somewhere, and start with a clean
# file but keep this around for reference. Or just disable in sites-enabled.
#
# Please see /usr/share/doc/nginx-doc/examples/ for more detailed examples.
##

##
# Tomcat setup
##
upstream tomcat {
    server 127.0.0.1:8080 fail_timeout=0;
}

# dev.sdruskat.net server configuration
#
server {
	listen 80 default_server; # Ipv4
	listen [::]:80 ipv6only=on; # IPv6
	
	root /var/www/dev.sdruskat.net;

	# Add index.php to the list if you are using PHP
	index index.html index.nginx-debian.html;

	server_name dev.sdruskat.net;

	location / {
		# First attempt to serve request as file, then
		# as directory, then fall back to displaying a 404.
		try_files $uri $uri/ =404;
	}

	# /lexicon forward to tomcat
	location /lexicon {
		include proxy_params;
		proxy_pass http://tomcat/lexicon;
	}


    listen [::]:443 ssl ipv6only=on; # managed by Certbot
    listen 443 ssl; # managed by Certbot
    ssl_certificate /etc/letsencrypt/live/dev.sdruskat.net/fullchain.pem; # managed by Certbot
    ssl_certificate_key /etc/letsencrypt/live/dev.sdruskat.net/privkey.pem; # managed by Certbot
    include /etc/letsencrypt/options-ssl-nginx.conf; # managed by Certbot
    ssl_dhparam /etc/letsencrypt/ssl-dhparams.pem; # managed by Certbot

}

# You should look at the following URL's in order to grasp a solid understanding
# of Nginx configuration files in order to fully unleash the power of Nginx.
# http://wiki.nginx.org/Pitfalls
# http://wiki.nginx.org/QuickStart
# http://wiki.nginx.org/Configuration
#
# Generally, you will want to move this file somewhere, and start with a clean
# file but keep this around for reference. Or just disable in sites-enabled.
#
# Please see /usr/share/doc/nginx-doc/examples/ for more detailed examples.
##

#
# dev.sdruskat.net server configuration
#
server {
	listen 80;
	listen [::]:80;

	root /var/www/forschungssoftware.org;

	# Add index.php to the list if you are using PHP
	index index.html index.nginx-debian.html;

	server_name forschungssoftware.org www.forschungssoftware.org;

	location = / {
		# First attempt to serve request as file, then
		# as directory, then fall back to displaying a 404.
		return 301 http://research-software.org/citation;
	}


    listen [::]:443 ssl ipv6only=on; # managed by Certbot
    listen 443 ssl; # managed by Certbot
    ssl_certificate /etc/letsencrypt/live/forschungssoftware.org/fullchain.pem; # managed by Certbot
    ssl_certificate_key /etc/letsencrypt/live/forschungssoftware.org/privkey.pem; # managed by Certbot
    include /etc/letsencrypt/options-ssl-nginx.conf; # managed by Certbot
    ssl_dhparam /etc/letsencrypt/ssl-dhparams.pem; # managed by Certbot

}

# Please see /usr/share/doc/nginx-doc/examples/ for more detailed examples.

# dev.sdruskat.net server configuration

server {
	listen 80;
	listen [::]:80;

	root /var/www/forschungssoftware.org;

	# Add index.php to the list if you are using PHP

	location = / {
		# First attempt to serve request as file, then
		# as directory, then fall back to displaying a 404.
		return 301 http://research-software.org/citation;
	}

    listen 443 ssl; # managed by Certbot

2018-02-23 11:50:31,805:INFO:certbot_nginx.configurator:Deployed Certificate to VirtualHost /etc/nginx/sites-enabled/dev.sdruskat.net for dev.sdruskat.net
2018-02-23 11:50:31,806:DEBUG:certbot_nginx.parser:Writing nginx conf tree to /etc/nginx/sites-enabled/dev.sdruskat.net:
##
# You should look at the following URL's in order to grasp a solid understanding
# of Nginx configuration files in order to fully unleash the power of Nginx.
# http://wiki.nginx.org/Pitfalls
# http://wiki.nginx.org/QuickStart
# http://wiki.nginx.org/Configuration
#
# Generally, you will want to move this file somewhere, and start with a clean
# file but keep this around for reference. Or just disable in sites-enabled.
#
# Please see /usr/share/doc/nginx-doc/examples/ for more detailed examples.
##

##
# Tomcat setup
##
upstream tomcat {
    server 127.0.0.1:8080 fail_timeout=0;
}

# dev.sdruskat.net server configuration
#
server {
#	listen 80 default_server; # Ipv4
#	listen [::]:80 ipv6only=on; # IPv6

	listen 80;
	listen [::]:80;
	
	root /var/www/dev.sdruskat.net;

	# Add index.php to the list if you are using PHP
	index index.html index.nginx-debian.html;

	server_name dev.sdruskat.net;

	location / {
		# First attempt to serve request as file, then
		# as directory, then fall back to displaying a 404.
		try_files $uri $uri/ =404;
	}

	# /lexicon forward to tomcat
	location /lexicon {
		include proxy_params;
		proxy_pass http://tomcat/lexicon;
	}


    listen [::]:443 ssl ipv6only=on; # managed by Certbot
    listen 443 ssl; # managed by Certbot
    ssl_certificate /etc/letsencrypt/live/dev.sdruskat.net/fullchain.pem; # managed by Certbot
    ssl_certificate_key /etc/letsencrypt/live/dev.sdruskat.net/privkey.pem; # managed by Certbot
    include /etc/letsencrypt/options-ssl-nginx.conf; # managed by Certbot
    ssl_dhparam /etc/letsencrypt/ssl-dhparams.pem; # managed by Certbot

}

##
# You should look at the following URL's in order to grasp a solid understanding
# of Nginx configuration files in order to fully unleash the power of Nginx.
# http://wiki.nginx.org/Pitfalls
# http://wiki.nginx.org/QuickStart
# http://wiki.nginx.org/Configuration
#
# Generally, you will want to move this file somewhere, and start with a clean
# file but keep this around for reference. Or just disable in sites-enabled.
#
# Please see /usr/share/doc/nginx-doc/examples/ for more detailed examples.
##

##
# Tomcat setup
##
upstream tomcat {
    server 127.0.0.1:8080 fail_timeout=0;
}

# dev.sdruskat.net server configuration
#
server {
#	listen 80 default_server; # Ipv4
#	listen [::]:80 ipv6only=on; # IPv6

	listen 80;
	listen [::]:80;
	
	root /var/www/dev.sdruskat.net;

	# Add index.php to the list if you are using PHP
	index index.html index.nginx-debian.html;

	server_name dev.sdruskat.net;

	location / {
		# First attempt to serve request as file, then
		# as directory, then fall back to displaying a 404.
		try_files $uri $uri/ =404;
	}

	# /lexicon forward to tomcat
	location /lexicon {
		include proxy_params;
		proxy_pass http://tomcat/lexicon;
	}


    listen [::]:443 ssl ipv6only=on; # managed by Certbot
    listen 443 ssl; # managed by Certbot
    ssl_certificate /etc/letsencrypt/live/dev.sdruskat.net/fullchain.pem; # managed by Certbot
    ssl_certificate_key /etc/letsencrypt/live/dev.sdruskat.net/privkey.pem; # managed by Certbot
    include /etc/letsencrypt/options-ssl-nginx.conf; # managed by Certbot
    ssl_dhparam /etc/letsencrypt/ssl-dhparams.pem; # managed by Certbot
